The paper presents a method for analyzing Markov Decision Processes (MDPs) without fully computing the value function or optimal policy. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, which deals with the development of intelligent agents and decision-making systems. Additionally, the paper's focus on MDPs and optimal policies suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, which deals with the development of algorithms that can learn from data. 

The paper's use of mathematical frameworks and analysis of state spaces suggests that it may also belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category, which deals with the development of robots and autonomous systems. The paper's focus on decision-making and optimization also suggests that it may belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category, which deals with the development of control systems and optimization algorithms. Finally, the paper's use of algorithms and analysis of data suggests that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category, which deals with the development of efficient algorithms and data structures.
